# TypeScript Standards

## Purpose
Maintain a strict, readable, and durable TypeScript codebase.

## Requirements
- use strict typing by default
- avoid `any` unless there is a clear boundary reason
- define explicit types for public contracts
- prefer small focused interfaces and type aliases
- use discriminated unions for variant states where helpful
- keep exported functions and classes explicitly typed
- validate untrusted external input at boundaries
- keep domain types separate from transport and persistence types
- prefer composition over inheritance
- avoid duplicate type definitions across layers
- keep functions small and intention-revealing

## Apply When
- writing or editing TypeScript
- designing module contracts
- mapping data across layers
